      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software must be developed and verified under a documented quality management system with version control, issue tracking, and formal release procedures appropriate for Class III device support.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver is maintained under ISO 9001-aligned QMS with full version control and audit trails. Achieved Gradation 3 due to absence of formal independent software validation report; required Gradation 4 for MRL 5. Gap documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal order-of-accuracy studies and method-of-manufactured-solutions (MMS) tests must confirm solver correctness for the governing equations relevant to rotating machinery hemolysis.",
      "rationale": "MMS studies confirm second-order spatial accuracy for Navier-Stokes terms. Hemolysis transport scalar equation verified to first order only; required second-order convergence not demonstrated. Achieves Gradation 3 against required Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) or equivalent Richardson extrapolation must be reported for all QoIs at each operating point with GCI < 5% on hemolysis index.",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study performed; hemolysis index GCI ranges 6–11% across operating points, exceeding the 5% threshold. Pressure-rise GCI < 3%. Discretization error is the primary numerical uncertainty contributor. Gradation 3 achieved; Gradation 4 required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match simulation boundary conditions within documented tolerances; fluid temperature, hematocrit, and rotational speed must be controlled and reported.",
      "rationale": "Bench experiments conducted at 37 °C ± 0.5 °C, hematocrit 33 ± 1%, and rotational speeds within ± 10 RPM of nominal. All boundary conditions traceable to experimental records. Gradation 3 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metrics (E%, NRMSE, or equivalent) must be computed for hemolysis index at all 5 operating points with uncertainty intervals on both simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "Normalised RMSE for hemolysis index is 18% across 5 operating points; individual point errors range 8–31%. Experimental uncertainty bands (95% CI) computed from triplicate runs. Simulation uncertainty from Monte Carlo ensemble. Gradation 3 achieved; Gradation 4 requires NRMSE < 10%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs predicted by the model (hemolysis index, shear stress exposure) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint and regulatory acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index (normalised index of hemolysis, NIH) is the direct regulatory QoI specified in ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance. Shear stress exposure time histories are the mechanistic intermediate. Full traceability from model output to clinical threshold established. Gradation 4 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, fluid, and operating envelope as the COU; extrapolation beyond validated range must be explicitly bounded.",
      "rationale": "Validation uses FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry identical to COU model. Fluid is bovine blood (not human); species difference introduces unquantified hemolysis model extrapolation. Operating envelope partially overlaps COU: 3 of 5 COU points within validated range. Gradation 3 achieved; Gradation 4 requires full envelope coverage with same fluid."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to residual norms below 1e-5 for all transport equations; round-off and floating-point sensitivity must be characterised.",
      "rationale": "All residuals converge to < 1e-6 within 2000 iterations at each operating point. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout. Floating-point sensitivity confirmed negligible via single/double comparison. Gradation 3 achieved and required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary condition application, turbulence model selection, and hemolysis model parameterisation must be documented in a simulation plan.",
      "rationale": "Simulation plan documented but independent review limited to internal peer; no external expert review conducted. Turbulence model selection (SST k-ω) justified by literature but sensitivity to model choice not fully explored. Hemolysis power-law constants from Giersiepen (1990) applied without recalibration. Gradation 2 achieved; Gradation 3 requires independent external review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The governing equations, turbulence closure, and hemolysis damage model must be appropriate for the flow regime and validated against published benchmark data for rotating blood-contacting devices.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment of model form adequacy was conducted by the credibility assessment team in consultation with two independent subject-matter experts in computational hemodynamics. The Reynolds-Averaged Navier-Stokes formulation with SST k-ω closure is well-established for turbomachinery flows in the Reynolds number regime of interest (Re ~ 10^4–10^5). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis accumulation model, while acknowledged to have limitations at low-shear exposure times, is the most widely cited model in the literature for centrifugal blood pump hemolysis prediction and has been used in multiple FDA-reviewed submissions. Published benchmark comparisons (Zhang et al. 2011, Hariharan et al. 2018) demonstrate qualitative agreement between SST k-ω predictions and PIV measurements in analogous geometries. The assessment team concluded that the model form is fit for purpose for this COU given the operating regime and the nature of the clinical decision, and that no alternative model form would provide materially superior predictive capability within the project timeline. This determination is based on expert judgment and literature synthesis rather than a formal quantitative level assignment, as the team assessed that the structured gradation rubric did not map cleanly onto the multi-component nature of model form adequacy for hemolysis simulation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters (fluid properties, boundary conditions, hemolysis model constants) must be characterised with uncertainty bounds; sensitivity analysis must identify dominant inputs.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification performed over 500 samples spanning fluid viscosity, density, hemolysis power-law exponent and coefficient, and inlet velocity profile. Sobol sensitivity indices computed; hemolysis exponent α is the dominant input (S_T = 0.61). Blood viscosity characterised from literature ranges. Gradation 3 achieved; Gradation 4 requires patient-specific or device-specific viscosity measurements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples must be representative of the intended patient population; blood source, storage conditions, and hematocrit must be controlled and reported.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood used as blood analogue; human blood not used due to regulatory and logistical constraints. Hematocrit controlled at 33 ± 1%. Storage time < 24 h post-collection. Species difference is a recognised limitation that reduces representativeness for human hemolysis prediction. Gradation 2 achieved; Gradation 3 requires human blood or validated analogue with demonstrated equivalence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters must be demonstrated equivalent to experimental conditions through direct measurement or documented mapping with uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Inlet velocity profiles mapped from PIV measurements at pump inlet plane; rotational speed matched to within ± 10 RPM. Outlet pressure boundary condition derived from experimental pressure tap measurements. Equivalency established for primary hydraulic parameters. Hemolysis model constants not re-derived from experimental data; equivalency for damage model inputs not formally demonstrated. Gradation 2 achieved; Gradation 3 requires formal equivalency demonstration for all QoI-sensitive inputs."
    }
  ],
